/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-direction","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> in z-direction","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>-direction"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The velocity of the ant can be found as follows:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mover><mi>v</mi><mo>→</mo></mover></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mover><mi>S</mi><mo>→</mo></mover></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>, from equation (1), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>v</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42213,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{8} \\mathrm{~km}$","$8 \\mathrm{~km}$","$6 \\mathrm{~km}$","$4 \\mathrm{~km}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/x09KkKDVL78uv7OqUXkfln4WjY-G5iFalTfiTWx_8og.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\therefore$ Displacement $=\\mathrm{R} \\sqrt{2}=2 \\sqrt{2}=\\sqrt{8} \\mathrm{~km}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42229,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>62</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>It is given that&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Differentiating,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>At</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42203,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}}_{\\mathrm{b}}=9+27=36 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}$\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/UlWcc8CSWTgLR9EOanua1cEkdCCj8kKsh9IUIVKGS5I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}}_{\\mathrm{b}}=36 \\times \\frac{1000}{36000}=10 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{sec} \\\\ & \\text { Time of flight }=\\frac{2 \\times 10}{10}=2 \\mathrm{sec} \\\\ & \\text { Range }=10 \\times 2=20 \\mathrm{~m}=2000 \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42293,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Draw&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mi>t</mi></math> curve&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/37e845a3-62e5-46c6-9a2b-f895202dda50-image.png\" style=\"width: 279px; height: 208px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>tan</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#247;</mo></math> above</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42211,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["40","80","30","70"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} \\text { Average speed } & =\\frac{\\text { total distance }}{\\text { time taken }} \\\\ & =\\frac{\\frac{80 \\times \\mathrm{t}}{2}+80 \\times 3 \\mathrm{t}}{4 \\mathrm{t}}=70 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr} .\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42306,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6501df47-b3da-4507-a3dc-e16968749785-image.png\" style=\"width: 192px; height: 153px;\" /></p><p>Distance = Area of |v| &ndash; t graph&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42268,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["When the elevator moves upward with constant acceleration","When the elevator moves downward with constant acceleration","When the elevator moves upward with uniform velocity","When the elevator moves downward with uniform velocity"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a57cf1c7-156f-435b-8550-5840447b0398-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 185px;\" /></p><p>When the pseudo force acting on the person is in opposite direction to the weight then the person will experience weight loss. The direction of the pseudo force is opposite to the direction of the frame of reference.</p><p>Hence, B&nbsp;is the correct answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42215,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$6.25 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2$","$12.5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2$","$9 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2$","$5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { Given, } 102.5=\\mathrm{u}+\\frac{\\mathrm{a}}{2}(2 \\mathrm{n}-1) \\& \\\\\n& 115=\\mathrm{u}+\\frac{\\mathrm{a}}{2}(2 \\mathrm{n}+3) \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow 102.5=\\mathrm{u}+\\mathrm{an}-\\frac{\\mathrm{a}}{2} \\& \\\\\n& 115=\\mathrm{u}+\\mathrm{an}+\\frac{3 \\mathrm{a}}{2} \\\\\n& 12.5=2 \\mathrm{a} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{a}=6.25 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42192,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["4.2","2.5","4.0","3.8"],"answer":0,"solution":"Time for first drop to fall 5 m:<br>$5 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 10 \\times t^2$ gives $t = 1$ s.<br>Since the first drop strikes when the sixth begins, there are 5 intervals: each interval $T = \\frac{1}{5} = 0.2$ s.<br>When drop 1 hits the ground (at $t = 1$ s), drop 4 has been falling for $t_4 = 1 - 3 \\times 0.2 = 0.4$ s.<br>Distance fallen by drop 4: $s_4 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 10 \\times (0.4)^2 = 0.8$ m.<br>Height of drop 4 above ground: $5 - 0.8 = 4.2$ m.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42194,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["82.5","20","62.5","92.5"],"answer":3,"solution":"During the first $2\\text{ s}$ of free fall, the paratrooper starts from rest ($u = 0$).<br>Velocity after $2\\text{ s}$ is $v_1 = u + gt = 0 + 10 \\times 2 = 20\\text{ m/s}$.<br>Distance covered during free fall is $h_1 = \\frac{1}{2}gt^2 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 10 \\times 2^2 = 20\\text{ m}$.<br>After opening the parachute, the paratrooper decelerates at $a = -3\\text{ m/s}^2$.<br>At a height of $10\\text{ m}$ from the ground, the final velocity is $v_2 = 5\\text{ m/s}$.<br>Let $h_2$ be the distance covered during deceleration until reaching $10\\text{ m}$ height.<br>Using $v_2^2 = v_1^2 + 2ah_2$:<br>$5^2 = 20^2 + 2(-3)h_2$<br>$25 = 400 - 6h_2$<br>$6h_2 = 375$<br>$h_2 = 62.5\\text{ m}$.<br>The total height of the airplane is the sum of the free fall distance, the deceleration distance, and the remaining height from the ground.<br>$H = h_1 + h_2 + 10 = 20 + 62.5 + 10 = 92.5\\text{ m}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42295,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9c7d996a-a670-44a0-a23d-f8b79a989420-image.png\" style=\"width: 93px; height: 149px;\" /></p><p>When lift is at rest</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>600</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p><p>When lift moves with downward acceleration. In frame of lift pseudo force will be in upward direction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2695c559-72b6-4cfe-be69-74ed8053609c-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 149px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>N</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>M</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>60</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>N</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>492</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42272,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>:</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>:</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Net force while going upward will be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>u</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Similarly,&nbsp;Net force while going downward&nbsp;will be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>d</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>40</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Since&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>u</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><msup><msub><mi>t</mi><mrow><mi>u</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>a</mi><mi>d</mi></msub><msup><msub><mi>t</mi><mi>d</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>t</mi><mrow><mi>u</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>t</mi><mi>d</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42232,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The formula to calculate the velocity of the ball after&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>&nbsp;is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>The formula to calculate the velocity of the ball after&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>&nbsp;is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Divide equation (1) by equation (2) to obtain the required ratio.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameters into equation (3) to calculate the required ratio.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>150</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>30</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>150</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>50</mn></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>120</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Comparing the above equation with the given expression, it can be written that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42185,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$85$","$150$","$129$","$125$"],"answer":3,"solution":"When the stone is dropped, it acquires the initial velocity of the balloon. Taking the upward direction as positive, the initial velocity of the stone is $u = 10$ m/s.<br><br>The displacement of the stone when it hits the ground is $S = -75$ m, and its acceleration is $a = -g = -10$ m/s$^2$.<br><br>Using the equation of motion $S = ut + \\dfrac{1}{2}at^2$:<br><br>$-75 = 10t - \\dfrac{1}{2}(10)t^2$<br><br>$-75 = 10t - 5t^2$<br><br>$5t^2 - 10t - 75 = 0$<br><br>$t^2 - 2t - 15 = 0$<br><br>$(t - 5)(t + 3) = 0$<br><br>Since time cannot be negative, $t = 5$ s.<br><br>During this time, the balloon continues to move upwards with a constant velocity of $10$ m/s. The distance travelled by the balloon in $5$ s is:<br><br>$d = v \\times t = 10 \\times 5 = 50$ m<br><br>The total height of the balloon when the stone hits the ground is:<br><br>$H = 75 + 50 = 125$ m<br><br>Answer: $125$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42349,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$S=f t$","$\\mathrm{S}=1 / 6 \\mathrm{ft}^2$","$\\mathrm{S}=1 / 2 \\mathrm{ft}^2$","None of these"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f44uaYu5WyQwBGx5gyyxOdjFgrfaZU9zGiMgi8e5BD0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{S}=\\frac{\\mathrm{ft}_1^2}{2} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{v}_0=\\sqrt{2 \\mathrm{Sf}}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nDuring retardation\n$$\nS_2=2 S\n$$\nDuring constant velocity\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 15 \\mathrm{~S}-3 \\mathrm{~S}=12 \\mathrm{~S}=\\mathrm{v}_0 \\mathrm{t} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{S}=\\frac{\\mathrm{ft}^2}{72}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":42219,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>5</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>x</mi></math> </p><p>Differentiating w.r.t time, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>β</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>β</mi></math></p><p>Differentiating w.r.t time again, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mtext>as</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42262,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Displacement covered by first ball,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>180</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Now, the second body gets only,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>.</p><p>Displacement covered by second will be same,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>80</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>80</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42202,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{p}}=\\mathrm{kt}, \\mathrm{k}$ is constant\n$\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{Q}}=\\mathrm{a}, \\mathrm{a}$ is constant\n$\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{QP}}=\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{Q}}-\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{p}}=\\mathrm{a}-\\mathrm{kt}$\nas initial velocities are not mentioned in question, so will have to assume two cases.\nCase-I\n$\\mathrm{u}_{\\mathrm{OP}}$ and $\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{QP}}$ in same direction\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/YVqoMWrcdKkZWOfDuL9SRjgzO469s7gZVsL26HNEZSE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nTotal number of crossing $=2$ Case-II\n$\\mathrm{u}_{\\mathrm{QP}}$ and $\\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{QP}}$ in opposite direction<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qhOC8SkrpuasljZGOfd0Kp0Rwz76-S4nM8eSmzX-5gQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\nTotal number of crossing $=3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42346,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$t^3$","$t^2$","$t$","$t^{1 / 2}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\frac{\\mathrm{d} x}{\\mathrm{dt}}=\\alpha \\int \\frac{\\mathrm{dx}}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{x}}}=\\int \\alpha \\mathrm{dt} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{x} \\alpha \\mathrm{t}^2$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":42356,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$12 \\mathrm{~m}$","$18 \\mathrm{~m}$","$24 \\mathrm{~m}$","$6 \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Energy $=$ Work done by force $(\\mathrm{F})$\n$$\n\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{~m} .(50)^2=(\\mathrm{F})(6) \\quad \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{F}=\\frac{2500 \\mathrm{~m}}{2 \\times 6}\n$$\nFor $\\mathrm{v}=100 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr} \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\mathrm{m}(100)^2=(\\mathrm{F})(\\mathrm{S})$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{~m}(100)^2=\\left(\\frac{2500 \\mathrm{~m}}{2 \\times 6}\\right) \\mathrm{S} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{S}=\\frac{100 \\times 100 \\times 6 \\times 2}{2500 \\times 2}=24 \\mathrm{~m}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":42189,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$18$","$28$","$38$","$48$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Velocity of car A, $v_A = 100$ km/h<br><br>Velocity of car B, $v_B = 80$ km/h<br><br>Velocity of the stone relative to car B is $v$. The velocity of the stone relative to the ground is $v_S = v_B + v = 80 + v$.<br><br>The velocity of the stone relative to car A is $v_{S/A} = v_S - v_A = (80 + v) - 100 = v - 20$.<br><br>The stone hits car A with a relative speed of $5$ m/s. Converting this speed to km/h:<br><br>$v_{S/A} = 5 \\times \\dfrac{18}{5} = 18$ km/h<br><br>Equating the relative speeds:<br><br>$v - 20 = 18 \\Rightarrow v = 38$ km/h<br><br>Answer: $38$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42244,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mi>g</mi><mi>R</mi></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mi>g</mi><mi>R</mi></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>g</mi><mi>R</mi></msqrt></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>As gravitational field is a conservative field and therefore mechanical energy will be conserved. Therefore,<br />Loss in PE = Gain in KE</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mtext>as</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi>g</mi><mi>R</mi></msqrt></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42312,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf0c2360-2edb-48fd-9cd2-1a2a98ace27e-image.png\" style=\"width: 228px; height: 188px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a591373a-964f-4c6d-ab78-3a75124520b0-image.png\" style=\"width: 215px; height: 182px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fb22bef0-50cb-49eb-993a-e72109dc81d6-image.png\" style=\"width: 216px; height: 177px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16cfc87f-9248-4d1b-9a02-63813f38b66b-image.png\" style=\"width: 227px; height: 184px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The particle is at rest initially.</p><p>So, the initial velocity&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p><p>The force on the charged particle in the uniform electric field,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>E</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>E</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>E</mi></mrow><mi>m</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Applying the velocity-displacement equation under constant acceleration,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>u</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>0</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>E</mi></mrow><mi>m</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>q</mi><mi>E</mi></mrow><mi>m</mi></mfrac><mi>x</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42193,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":0,"solution":"The v-x graph shows velocity decreasing linearly with distance. Using kinematic equation $v^2 = v_0^2 + 2ax$, we can establish the relationship between acceleration and position. <br>From the linear v-x relationship, differentiating using $a = v\\frac{dv}{dx}$ yields acceleration that is linearly proportional to distance from the origin. <br>The a-x graph shows a straight line passing through the origin with positive slope, indicating that acceleration increases linearly with distance while remaining positive throughout the motion.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42357,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$3 t \\sqrt{\\alpha^2+\\beta^2}$","$3 t^2 \\sqrt{\\alpha^2+\\beta^2}$","$\\mathrm{t}^2 \\sqrt{\\alpha^2+\\beta^2}$","$\\sqrt{\\alpha^2+\\beta^2}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$V_x=\\frac{d x}{d t}=3 \\alpha t^2, V_y=\\frac{d y}{d t}=3 \\beta t^2$\n$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}}=\\sqrt{\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{x}^2}+\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{y}^2}}=3 \\mathrm{t}^2 \\sqrt{\\alpha^2+\\beta^2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":42352,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Motion In One Dimension","question":"","options":["$\\frac{2 \\mathrm{H}}{\\mathrm{A}-\\mathrm{B}}$","$\\frac{H}{A+B}$","$\\frac{H}{2(A+B)}$","$\\frac{H}{A-B}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& (A+B)=d=H \\\\\n& d=\\left(\\begin{array}{c}\nH \\\\\nA+B\n\\end{array}\\right) .\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null}]